text.inkscape:label: usage notes
text.tspan: there are two "target" groups in this file, one for either eye.
these are are 10cm x 10cm squares with 4mm circles on the midpoint of each edge, plus the center. this
is intended to line up with the target grid that comes with the 4"/10cm embroidery hoop that seems to be
the entry level machine
note that the eyes are not symmetrical because the catchlights are in different places on either eye.
some people prefer one way or the other. if you prefer them symmetrical, then pick one or the other
and mirror the eye in the embroidery machine
when you export the embroidery file, you generally want to also emit the bounding box of the target along
with all of the actual design. this forces the machine to keep the design in the center of the hoop so it's
easier to get the embroidery to land where you want it
i do it this way because i'm insane and drop the embroidery on to the pattern rather than the normal way
where you do the embroidery and then make the pattern fit wherever the embroidery happened to land
to actually export the designs, decide which eye you want to export. pick the arrow tool then open the
objects/layers pane in inkscape. copy the bounding-box layer under the appropriate (side) eye target group
plus the entire (direction) eye group (hint: click the target, ctrl-click the eye group), open a new inkscape
document, paste the objects, then save as whichever format your embroidery machine prefers
DO NOT USE SAVE AS OR SAVE A COPY!
these designs are for the standard three eyelash with oval shape eye, which is suitable for Pinkie, Rainbow,
Starlight, most random background mares, and can be adapted to stallions by hiding the eyelashes.
they include the following layers and are intended to be run in this order:
* a straight stitch around the perimeter of the eye to stick stabilizer down
* a ~1mm^2 underlay grid to stabilize the fabric
* the sclera (whites) fill
* the iris (colorful part) with four distinct regions
the relative lightness of each section of the iris should be followed, from darkest to lightest: top, bottom,
middle ("major"), bottom-middle ("minor")
this design does not support gradients to more closely match show style, sorry
* the pupil (black)
* catchlights (white ovals)
* the eyelashes (black)
* the stroke along the top of the eye (black)
* the machine should try to do the bounding box in bright red. just skip this
each of these features has a small but minimal amount of overlap with the neighboring features to avoid
gaps while keeping the embroidery relatively thin so the machine doesn't have to punch through several
layers of thread and it remains more flexible
there is an alternate set of iris shapes if you want fills instead of satin. they result in the same basic shape
just one's satin and the other is fill; satin looks better imo but you do you. if you want this, hide both of
the satin iris layers and unhide both of the fill iris layers
this design is intended to be run at the size it's presented, which is ~4" on edge. you can probably get
away with 50% scale, but you may have issues with the small feature size. if you have a bigger hoop, you
probably haver better software than i do
be prepared to adjust the params. these settings work on my machine, yours may require different settings
depending on your minky, stabilizer, thread tension, phase of the moon, etc...
